<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="63" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="20.[111,647,691,1130]" pageId="20" pageNumber="63">
A rather large specimen consists of a single fragment of distorted wood (
<figureCitation box="[311,392,723,750]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="15.[115,124,1635,1652]" captionTargetId="figure-29@16.[178,786,587,913]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIG. 9. — Silicified plants from the Permian of Sardinia: A, Cordaixylon sp., transverse section of a partly decorticated small stem with a solid parenchymatous pith; on the left the closely associated rachis (P) with several xylem bundles may represent a petiole of the same plant (SAR24B4L13);B, Cordaites leaves associated with Pecopteris pinnules;the broadest leaf (CC) with interfascicular scleren-" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4607883" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4607883/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="63">Fig. 9A</figureCitation>
); however characteristic features are preserved: the files of secondary xylem tracheids (
<quantity box="[224,332,786,813]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="20" pageNumber="63" unit="mm" value="40.0" valueMax="50.0" valueMin="30.0">30-50 µm</quantity>
in diameter) are separated by narrow (uniseriate) rays of variable height (2 to 20 cells) (
<figureCitation box="[178,290,849,876]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="15.[115,124,1635,1652]" captionTargetId="figure-29@16.[178,786,587,913]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIG. 9. — Silicified plants from the Permian of Sardinia: A, Cordaixylon sp., transverse section of a partly decorticated small stem with a solid parenchymatous pith; on the left the closely associated rachis (P) with several xylem bundles may represent a petiole of the same plant (SAR24B4L13);B, Cordaites leaves associated with Pecopteris pinnules;the broadest leaf (CC) with interfascicular scleren-" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4607883" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4607883/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="63">Fig. 9B, D</figureCitation>
); pitting, restricted to radial walls, shows uni- to biseriate rows of crowded circular bordered pits (
<figureCitation box="[270,354,913,940]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="15.[115,124,1635,1652]" captionTargetId="figure-29@16.[178,786,587,913]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIG. 9. — Silicified plants from the Permian of Sardinia: A, Cordaixylon sp., transverse section of a partly decorticated small stem with a solid parenchymatous pith; on the left the closely associated rachis (P) with several xylem bundles may represent a petiole of the same plant (SAR24B4L13);B, Cordaites leaves associated with Pecopteris pinnules;the broadest leaf (CC) with interfascicular scleren-" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4607883" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4607883/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="63">Fig. 9C</figureCitation>
). This anatomy is similar to that of woody trunks of 
<taxonomicName authority="Unger" authorityName="Unger" box="[358,590,944,971]" class="Pinopsida" family="Araucariaceae" genus="Dadoxylon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="20" pageNumber="63" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rollei">
<emphasis box="[358,520,944,970]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="63">Dadoxylon rollei</emphasis>
Unger
</taxonomicName>
from the Lower Permian of 
<collectingCountry box="[352,453,976,1003]" name="Germany" pageId="20" pageNumber="63">Germany</collectingCountry>
and from Autun. 
<bibRefCitation author="MARGUERIER J." box="[113,318,1008,1035]" pageId="20" pageNumber="63" pagination="77 - 97" refId="ref13242" refString="MARGUERIER J. 1971. - A propos d'un bois fossile de l'Autunien d'Autun: Dadoxylon rollei Unger, bois presume de coniferophyte. Comptes Rendus du 96 e Congres national des Societes Savantes, Toulouse, Sciences 5: 77 - 97." type="journal article" year="1971">Marguerier (1971)</bibRefCitation>
, who investigated trunks from Autun, consider that characteristics of tracheid pittings of such woods suggest affinities with walchian conifers rather than with cordaites.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
